statement:
The augmented matrix below for a linear system is put in reduced row
echelon form with row operations. Write one of the following:

\begin{itemize}
\itemsep1pt\parskip0pt\parsep0pt
\item
  the solution if it is unique
\item
  all solutions if there are more than one
\item
  state that there are no solutions.
\end{itemize}

\textbf{(e)}

\begin{align*}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}1 & 0 & 2 & -1 \\ 0 & 1 & 2 & -2 \end{array}\right. \left| \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \end{array}\right]\end{align*}

sols:
For the matrix,

\begin{align*}\left[\begin{array}{cccc}1 & 0 & 2 & -1 \\ 0 & 1 & 2 & -2 \end{array}\right. \left| \begin{array}{c} 1 \\ 2 \end{array}\right]\end{align*}

we have two more columns than rows (the matrix is rank deficient) and so
we have two free variables. Let \emph{x}\textsubscript{3} and
\emph{x}\textsubscript{4} be those variables. Then from row 2 we have,

\begin{align*}
x_2+2x_3-2x_4&=2\\
x_2&=2-2x_3+2x_4\end{align*}

and from row 1 we have,

\begin{align*}
x_1+2x_3-x_4&=1\\
x_1&=1-2x_3+x_4.\end{align*}

Therefore we have two null vectors,

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
-2\\
-2\\
1\\
0
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

and

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2\\
0\\
1
\end{bmatrix}\end{align*}

as well as a particular solution

\begin{align*}\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2\\
0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

Therefore the solution is

\begin{align*}\mathbf{x}=
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2\\
0\\
0
\end{bmatrix}
+s
\begin{bmatrix}
-2\\
-2\\
1\\
0
\end{bmatrix}
+t
\begin{bmatrix}
1\\
2\\
0\\
1
\end{bmatrix}.\end{align*}

There are an infinite number of solutions.
